comment.author: 58880069@N07
comment.text: Stamp of English bookbinder Robert Riviere: "Bound by Riviere". Rivière, Robert, 1808-1882 was an English bookbinder of Huguenot descent, active in Bath from 1829 to ca. 1840 when he relocated his business to London. In 1881, he bequeathed his business to the eldest son of the second daughter, Mr. Percival Calkin, who had been taken into partnership by his grandfather , when the style of the firm was altered to Robert Riviere & Son. The Riviere bindings are remarkable in the forwarding, the finish and delicacy of the tooling and because of the quality of the materials. Taking into consideration the fact that Riviere was entirely self-taught, his bindings are wonderful specimens of artistic taste, skill, and perseverance. Riviere bindings may be approximately dated by the stamped signature inside the front covers: Bound by R. Riviere, Bath means 1829-32; Bound by R. Riviere means 1832-40; Bound by Riviere means 1840-c.1860; Bound by Riviere & Son means after 1880. The heirs of George Bayntun of Bath bought out Riviere & Sons.

comment.author: 58880069@N07
comment.text: Engraved vignette depicting a life-drawing class about to begin at Bologna's Accademia Clementina. At the center, the master directs the model's pose while the students talk animatedly. A background niche holds a plaster model or drawing of the ancient Roman sculpture, the Farnese Hercules. The master's features, particularly his large nose, suggest that Zanotti may have portrayed himself here. To continue the Bolognese painting tradition established by the Carracci, particularly its emphasis on life drawing from the nude, Zanotti helped to found the Accademia Clementina in 1710. Life drawing was the basis of instruction at the Accademia, so the subject was appropriate for this drawing, the basis for an engraved frontispiece to Zanotti's Storia dell'Accademia Clementina di Bologna of 1739. Zanotti began by sketching with black chalk, then went over those lines with pen and ink. His thought process is evident in the chalk underdrawing of the lamp and its rope, which he initially drew farther to the left. Zanotti, who probably also made the engraving, went over the principal outlines with the stylus to transfer the design to the copperplate for engraving. Cf. this description of a similar engraving at the J. Paul Getty Museum.

comment.text:
ELISABETHA SOPHIA MARIA VERWITTWETE HERZOGINN ZU BR. U. LUN: [Engraved armorial bookplate of Elisabeth Sophie Marie (1683-1767), Herzogin zu Braunschweig und Lüneburg, wife of August Wilhelm (1662-1731), Herzog zu Braunschweig und Lüneburg. By the adjective "verwittwete" (dowager), it dates from after August Wilhelm's death in 1731. Elisabeth Sophie Marie was notable for her collection of Bibles in both print and ms.
"She ... amassed a truly magnificent collection, which was housed in the ducal castle at Brunswick. She employed Georg Ludolph Otto Knoch to make a tabulated list of these Bibles, which is admirably laid out in five columns across the page, giving first the number of the book in the collection, then the description (including size and condition), the date, the place of printing, and the printer's name. The layout clearly impressed contemporaries, for it was imitated in Andrew Ducarel's bibliography of Bibles printed at London in 1777. The duchess certainly took an interest in the work, because she inscribed the Broxbourne copy to the bibliographer David Clement."--G. Pollard and A. Ehrman, The Distribution of Books by Catalogue from the Invention of Printing to A.D. 1800 (Cambridge, 1965), p. 335.
DNB heading: Elisabeth Sophie Marie Braunschweig-Lüneburg, Herzogin 1683-1767]

comment.text: Stamp of binder Lucien Broca: "Bound by L. Broca". Master binder Lucien Broca was a Frenchman who came to London to work for Antoine Chatelin, and from 1876 to 1889 he was in partnership with Simon Kaufmann. From 1890 he appears under his own name in Shaftesbury Avenue, and in 1901 he was at Percy Street, calling himself an "Art Binder." He was recognized as a superb trade finisher, and Marianne Tidcombe has confirmed that he actually executed most of Sarah Prideaux's bindings from the mid-1890s. Cf. this website.

In ink: Geo. T. Davidson [Autograph of George Trimble Davidson (b. 1863), son of M.O. Davidson. The younger Davidson was a lawyer and notable member of New York society (cf. his entry in The National Cyclopaedia of American Biography, v. 4 (New York: J. White & Co., 1893). He took his law degree from Columbia in 1885 and may have been accused of misappropriation of funds in 1901 (cf. "Suit Over Trust Fund" in The New York Times 4 June 1901, p. 5). His appearances in the society pages were happier. According to his entry in Leslie's History of the Greater New York, he was "prominent in the arrangement of a number of high social affairs," including the reception of the Infanta Eulalia of Spain, at which his behavior was cause for note in the New York Times of 28 May 1893 (p. 5):
The members of the Committee of One Hundred were much amused at the behavior of one of their number, George Trimble Davidson. On the day that the Princess arrived Mr. Davidson took her hand and impressed upon it a kiss. At the ball Mr. Davidson, according to the story of one who witnessed it, approached the Infanta beaming. "How are you, Princess?" he said. "You remember me, don't you? I am the man who first kissed your hand at the reception yesterday." Later, as the Princess was coming slowly down the room at the head of the procession, Mr. Davidson approached her and, touching her slightly on the arm, said; "Princess, allow me to introduce a friend of mine. The whole procession stopped and, as the Infanta looked a little surprised, Mr. Davidson continued: "You remember me, don't you?" The Princess smiled, Mr. Davidson looked supremely happy, and the procession moved on.
He is likely the author of The Moderns: A Tale of New York (New York: Stokes, 1901), favorably reviewed as "just the thing for summer reading" in The Public Library Bulletin 1.2 (August 1901), p. 34. Among his other distinctions, a recipe for oysters bears his name.]

comment.text: The three clam shells with the rampant lion is indeed the Russell family crest. Given the potentially commonplace nature of this name, exact identification could be difficult, but two particularly famous Diana Russells have come up: Diana Russell, Duchess of Bedford (1710-1735) (en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diana_Russell,_Duchess_of_Bedford) and the important South African feminist writer Diana E.H. Russell (1938-present) (en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diana_E._H._Russell). If it is either of these two, it is more likely to be the former given the apparent age of the bookplate and the book it is pasted on. Knowing the date of the book will help immensely in determining whether it is Lady Bedford's, or if the search must focus on a new "Diana Russell."
